Here's a minimal API endpoint that accepts multiple images plus a description field via `multipart/form-data`:

```csharp
// In Program.cs

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size (default is ~30MB)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    options.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 50 * 1024 * 1024; // 50 MB
});

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (
    [FromForm] IFormFileCollection files,
    [FromForm] string description,
    CancellationToken ct) =>
{
    if (files.Count == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No files uploaded.");

    var allowed = new[] { "image/jpeg", "image/png", "image/gif", "image/webp" };
    var savedPaths = new List<string>();

    foreach (var file in files)
    {
        if (!allowed.Contains(file.ContentType))
            return Results.BadRequest($"Unsupported type: {file.ContentType}");

        var savePath = Path.Combine("uploads", $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}");
        Directory.CreateDirectory("uploads");

        await using var stream = File.Create(savePath);
        await file.CopyToAsync(stream, ct);
        savedPaths.Add(savePath);
    }

    return Results.Ok(new
    {
        Description = description,
        FileCount = files.Count,
        Paths = savedPaths
    });
})
.DisableAntiforgery()          // required for form binding in minimal APIs
.WithName("UploadImages");

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **`[FromForm]`** — binds both the file collection and the text field from the same `multipart/form-data` request.
- **`ConfigureKestrel`** — raises the body size limit to 50 MB. Without this, requests over ~30 MB are rejected.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** — minimal APIs enforce antiforgery on form bindings by default; disable it for API-style endpoints (or supply tokens if you need CSRF protection).
- **Content-type check** — validates each file is an allowed image MIME type.

**Example `curl` call:**

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/upload \
  -F "description=Product photos" \
  -F "files=@photo1.jpg" \
  -F "files=@photo2.png"
```

If you'd rather use a strongly-typed model instead of individual `[FromForm]` parameters:

```csharp
public record UploadRequest(IFormFileCollection Files, string Description);

app.MapPost("/upload", async ([FromForm] UploadRequest req, CancellationToken ct) =>
{
    // req.Files and req.Description are bound automatically
    // ...same logic as above...
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```
